Crashing waves from storm swells may melt Antarctic sea ice far faster than previously believed.

Researchers have found that large ocean waves can flow through ice packs for hundreds of miles before their force is weakened.

Experiments
 in Antarctica by a New Zealand-led team revealed these wave movements 
are strong enough to break up the ice and trigger melting.

